Merival partitioned objects have tens of thousands (about 120K) subpartitions each. This is due to the load process. Each workernode does a direct path write (it must do this due to compression). As separate inserts can't insert append in to the same segment, they all write in to separate SUB_PARTITIONS. So every PARTITION_ID has about 32 SUB_PARTITION_IDs.
Latest Bug status - Bug 25349329 - CKPT LOOPING BLOCKING 300 PROCESSES ON 'ENQ: KO - FAST OBJECT CHECKPOINT'

With direct path read, every object involved has to be checkpointed before read to ensure there are no dirty buffers still in a cache in the cluster. To do this kxfrFlushObjs() will build a list of all objects and call kcbcbo() with these objects to message each CKPT. If the object(s) involved has many (in customer case hundreds of thousands) partitions, it will lead to a lot of messaging to CKPT, each message can carry up to KCBO_CH_MAX_CNT (1000 in 11.2) messages. This means for every query in the customer environment hundreds of messages were being sent for which CKPT had to consume, get the KO enqueue, check the object for dirty buffers, add the ckpt entry, post dbwr, wait for post
back, and perform post processing - this completely overloaded CKPT with so many partitions involved and lead to 'enq: KO - fast object checkpoint' delays.

If it is desired that any multi object/partition flush should use global cache checkpoints instead of object checkpoints then a user can set _dss_flush_cache=TRUE, this will lead to thread checkpoint for all multi object flushes under PX.

Object checkpoints are far more efficient than thread checkpoints, so new parameter _dss_flush_cache_threshold is introduced to tune this to the specific environment. A user can set _dss_flush_cache_threshold to the number of objects before we consider a cache (thread) checkpoint, and then only if cache checkpoints are enabled via _dss_flush_cache would a thread checkpoint be performed.
